===Verb===
{{en-verb|holds on|holding on|held on}}

# To [[grasp]] or [[grip]] firmly.
#: {{ux|en|'''Hold on''' tightly to the railing.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[keep]]; to [[store]] something for someone.
#: {{ux|en|'''Hold on''' to my umbrella while I ride the roller coaster.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} [[wait|Wait]] a short [[while]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Hold on''' while I get my coat.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1922|author={{w|Ben Travers}}| chapter=5| title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1521052W A Cuckoo in the Nest]| passage=The departure was not unduly prolonged. In the road Mr. Love and the driver favoured the company with a brief chanty running. “Got it?—No, I ain't, ''''old on''',—Got it? Got it?—No, ''''old on''' sir.”}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To remain [[loyal]].
#: {{ux|en|He didn't give up his fandom when others did; he '''held on'''.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[persist]].
#* {{RQ:Swift Some Arguments Against Enlarging the Power of Bishops}}
#*: This trade '''held on''' for many years.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2010|author=Sam Sheringham|work=BBC| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9308904.stm Liverpool 0-1 Wolverhampton]| passage=That scare aside, Wolves had little trouble in '''holding on''' for their first league away win of the season and their first over the Reds since little-known striker Steve Mardenborough gave them a victory at Anfield in January 1984.}}

====Usage notes====
This verbal phrase is technically intransitive, but it almost always takes an indirect object in a transitive sense by means of the word "to".

